    <page>
        <question id="bonding_response_q1">
        <body>

            <p>How would you explain what happens to a salt crystal that remains in a
                    non<?oxy_delete author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103219-0500" content="-"?>polar
                    solvent or a protein that finds itself buried in a sea of
                    lipid<?oxy_insert_start author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103253-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>?</p>
                   
        </body>
            <short_answer id="bonding_response_a1"/>
           
        <part>
            <response input="bonding_response_a1" match="*" score="1"/>
           <!-- <hint>You may want to think about what would happen if a certain property were different. </hint>
            <hint>Make sure you write an explanation for each of the properties</hint>-->
            <explanation>
                <p>The salt crystal won’t dissolve because the
                        non<?oxy_delete author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103336-0500" content="-"?>polar
                        solvent cannot interact favorably with the individual ions. A water soluble
                        protein, if found in a sea of
                        lipid<?oxy_insert_start author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103350-0500"?>s,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        is likely to
                        unfold<?oxy_insert_start author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103355-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        because the
                        non<?oxy_delete author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103358-0500" content="-"?>polar
                        residues that are in the core of the protein are no longer driven to the
                        core by the hydrophobic effect; they are “solvated” by the
                        non<?oxy_delete author="michellemyers" timestamp="20120227T103414-0500" content="-"?>polar
                        part of the membrane. </p>
            </explanation>
        </part>
